ODE VIII.

Quinctius Hirpinus was a man of great wealth, and of an anx- ious and timid character. He made himself unhappy by dreading changes and civil commotions, which might endanger his posses· sions. Horace offers to him, in this beautiful ode, the same kind of consolation which he frequently gives to others in trouble. He exhorts them not to be anxious about futurity3 since life is too short to have any portion of it wasted in unavailing anxieties. Old age and infirmities will soon deprive them of the power of enjoy- ing the blessings they possess.
